
GROOP.US

Described by Stan and Andrew Wasserman of the Centrality Journal blog.

URL = http://groop.us


"We read about a site, groop.us, that visualizes and groups people by tagging HTML documents. Currently the service is available to a select group of beta testers, and there seems to be some discussions going on through the Del.icio.us mail service.

"GROOP.US is a web service to visualize your social context based on the tags you have used. It shows your areas of interests and then relates people with similar interests to groups with shared tags and resources."

It is a self proclaimed, "clustering tool". To us it seems like a last.fm type thing for documents and web addresses instead of music. It attempts to create a neighborhood full of people who share your intrest."
(http://www.centralityjournal.com/archives/groopus.html)

